Fixes issue dotnet/runtime#57472

Main pr dotnet/runtime#57479

Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

## Background and Motivation

The `ForAttributeWithMetadataName` with `IIncrementalGenerator` is the prefered approach to generating source in the most efficient manner possible. To take full advantage of this new approach, this requires a shift in mentality that necessitates abandoning inefficient code inspection methods such as looks for classes that implement certain interfaces. This in turn often means creating more attributes and using the combination several attributes to generate the final source.

The class `Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.IncrementalValueProviderExtensions` currently provides several useful extension methods that can be used to transform the results of several calls to `ForAttributeWithMetadataName` including, and especially, `Combine<TLeft, TRight>(this IncrementalValueProvider<TLeft> provider1, IncrementalValueProvider<TRight> provider2)`.

A single `Combine` or two isn't much of an issue, however when several combines are chained, the resulting `IncrementalValuesProvider` ends with a convulated Tuple that is hard to manage.

As little as 4 combine operations are needed to end up with a incremental value provider like this:
`IncrementalValueProvider<((((T1, T2), T3), T4), T5)>`
Which if left unnamed in a consuming method ends up looking like this:
```
T1 => value.Item1.Item1.Item1.Item1
T2 => value.Item1.Item1.Item1.Item2
T3 => value.Item1.Item1.Item2
T4 => value.Item1.Item2
T5 => value.Item2
```

## Proposed API

Something similar to this would allow us to easily unwind the results of several combines.
```cs
internal static class ValueExtensions
{
    public static (T1 T1, T2 T2, T3 T3) Flatten<T1, T2, T3>(this ((T1 T1, T2 T2) _, T3 T3) root)
    {
        return (root._.T1, root._.T2, root.T3);
    }

    public static (T1 T1, T2 T2, T3 T3, T4 T4) Flatten<T1, T2, T3, T4>(this (((T1 T1, T2 T2) _, T3 T3) _, T4 T4) root)
    {
        return (root._._.T1, root._._.T2, root._.T3, root.T4);
    }

    public static (T1 T1, T2 T2, T3 T3, T4 T4, T5 T5) Flatten<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5>(this ((((T1 T1, T2 T2) _, T3 T3) _, T4 T4) _, T5 T5) root)
    {
        return (root._._._.T1, root._._._.T2, root._._.T3, root._.T4, root.T5);
    }

    public static (T1 T1, T2 T2, T3 T3, T4 T4, T5 T5, T6 T6) Flatten<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6>(this (((((T1 T1, T2 T2) _, T3 T3) _, T4 T4) _, T5 T5) _, T6 T6) root)
    {
        return (root._._._._.T1, root._._._._.T2, root._._._.T3, root._._.T4, root._.T5, root.T6);
    }

    public static (T1 T1, T2 T2, T3 T3, T4 T4, T5 T5, T6 T6, T7 T7) Flatten<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7>(this ((((((T1 T1, T2 T2) _, T3 T3) _, T4 T4) _, T5 T5) _, T6 T6) _, T7 T7) root)
    {
        return (root._._._._._.T1, root._._._._._.T2, root._._._._.T3, root._._._.T4, root._._.T5, root._.T6, root.T7);
    }

    public static (T1 T1, T2 T2, T3 T3, T4 T4, T5 T5, T6 T6, T7 T7, T8 T8) Flatten<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8>(this (((((((T1 T1, T2 T2) _, T3 T3) _, T4 T4) _, T5 T5) _, T6 T6) _, T7 T7) _, T8 T8) root)
    {
        return (root._._._._._._.T1, root._._._._._._.T2, root._._._._._.T3, root._._._._.T4, root._._._.T5, root._._.T6, root._.T7, root.T8);
    }

    public static (T1 T1, T2 T2, T3 T3, T4 T4, T5 T5, T6 T6, T7 T7, T8 T8, T9 T9) Flatten<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8, T9>(this ((((((((T1 T1, T2 T2) _, T3 T3) _, T4 T4) _, T5 T5) _, T6 T6) _, T7 T7) _, T8 T8) _, T9 T9) root)
    {
        return (root._._._._._._._.T1, root._._._._._._._.T2, root._._._._._._.T3, root._._._._._.T4, root._._._._.T5, root._._._.T6, root._._.T7, root._.T8, root.T9);
    }

    public static (T1 T1, T2 T2, T3 T3, T4 T4, T5 T5, T6 T6, T7 T7, T8 T8, T9 T9, T10 T10) Flatten<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8, T9, T10>(this (((((((((T1 T1, T2 T2) _, T3 T3) _, T4 T4) _, T5 T5) _, T6 T6) _, T7 T7) _, T8 T8) _, T9 T9) _, T10 T10) root)
    {
        return (root._._._._._._._._.T1, root._._._._._._._._.T2, root._._._._._._._.T3, root._._._._._._.T4, root._._._._._.T5, root._._._._.T6, root._._._.T7, root._._.T8, root._.T9, root.T10);
    }
}
```
## Usage Examples

Given the context `IncrementalGeneratorInitializationContext context` in the `Initialize` method of an `IIncrementalGenerator`, the method `GenerateSource` passed as `context.RegisterSourceOutput(pipeline, GenerateSource)` could then do the following:
```cs
private static void GeneratedSource(SourceProductionContext context, ((((T1 T1, T2 T2) Child, T3 T3) Child, T4 T4) Child, T5 T5) root)
{
    var values = root.Flatten();
    /*
    Makes values available as:
    values.T1
    values.T2
    values.T3
    values.T4
    values.T5
    */
}
```

Though thanks to automatic descontructors for Tuples, the following can easily be done as well:
```cs
private static void GeneratedSource(SourceProductionContext context, ((((T1 T1, T2 T2) Child, T3 T3) Child, T4 T4) Child, T5 T5) root)
{
    var (t1, t2, t3, t4, t5) = root.Flatten();
}
```

## Alternative Designs

A better approach would be a method that directly acts on an `IncrementalValueProvider` transforming it from `IncrementalValueProvider<((((T1, T2), T3), T4), T5)>` to `IncrementalValueProvider<(T1, T2, T3, T4, T5)>` and could be called as such:
```cs
provider1.Combine(provider2).Combine(provider3).Combine(provider4).Combine(provider5).Flatten();
```

But that requires access and understanding of the Roslyn internal APIs which I'm not sufficiently familiar with.

## Risks

This would be an additive to the current API therefore involves little to no risk.
